photo.title: Financial District from Coit Tower, Pioneer Park, Telegraph Hill, San Francisco, Ca. USA

description._content: To British eyes, US urban zoning like this looks bizarre. The foreground comprises residential streets of three-storey houses with the characteristic San Francisco bay windows (themselves reminiscent of British 20th Century suburban architecture), blending into a narrow band of two-storey office buildings. Then, as abruptly as crossing Washington Street, there rises a wall of high-rise towers including the 48-storey Transamerica Pyramid. Designed by William Pereira & Associates and built 1969-72 for the Transamerica Corporation, the distinctive 260m-tall Transamerica Pyramid was once ranked amongst the world's five tallest buildings; it's now 'merely' the tallest in San Francisco, clearly visible from across the region. It was nearly the world's second tallest, at 305 m (1,000 feet), but the City's Planning Commission was concerned about the view from Nob Hill, off the right of the image. Planning concerns also inspired its tapered shape, which reduces the building's apparent shadow and allows more light to penetrate to street level. The 'wings' rising from the 29th floor accommodate unavoidably vertical elements of the building: two elevator shafts on the east, and a stairwell and a smoke tower on the west. To the immediate right of the Pyramid is Montgomery Street, the original heart of the Financial District and "the Wall Street of the West". As recently as 1830 it was the waterfront, at which ships were able to moor; everything to the left is reclaimed land. Needless to say, the buildings of the Financial District were somewhat smaller in the 19th Century; the 'Manhattanization' of San Francisco didn't occur until the 1960s and 70s. [Image features several notes]

photo.title: Alcatraz and the Cap Delgado (Call Sign: A8FB9)

description._content:
West she goes, towards the Golden Gate
Orange hull headed towards the orange bridge
Then into the vast expanse that lies beyond

West she goes, past the Rock
Its prison cells long ago abandoned
Its hallways now full of tourists

West she goes, past hills that have seen
Generations of ships, some carried by the wind
Others driven by steam, pass before them

West she goes, racing towards the setting sun
Laden with the world’s commerce upon her back
Stacked high in little boxes

West she goes, one small cog
In the giant wheel of world commerce
West she goes

West she goes, towards the Golden Gate
Into the setting sun
West she goes

photo.title: Just Don't Fall!

description._content: For a number of years I parlayed my Air Force electronics training (from when I was enlisted) into a civilian career in wireless communications. This took me to many mountain tops in Northern California, and as you can see in this photograph, many building tops as well. In this shot, I am on top of 101 California in the Financial District, looking down on Pine Street. Market Street is seen in the lower left corner of the shot. 101 California Street reaches up some 600 feet (183 meters) and from this vantage point, I am about 10 feet below the very top of the building. photo.title: 101 California Street

description._content: This late-modernist skyscraper was captured in July 2009 with my Nikon D90 in the downtown Financial District of San Francisco, California.  101 California Street is another of San Francisco's highrises completed in the 1980s (in 1982) and it is the perfect contrast of the new vs. the old architecture that is rampant throughout the historical city.  I really liked the way this skyscraper turned out with the elements of the bright sun and the shadow created from surrounding other highrises.  I love the colors of the building to the left just barely leaning its way into the frame and I had to include it.  This is the 8th tallest skyscraper in San Francisco but will move down a spot when the new Transbay Terminal Tower is built (projected to start in 2014).  Enjoy!

photo.title: San Francisco - Financial District: 101 California Street and 388 Market Street Building

description._content:
101 California Street (right), also known as the  the Itel Building, was built in 1982 by Johnson/Burgee Architects.  The 48-story tower is cylindrical in shape with articulated edges of alternating bands of granite and glass featuring a seven-story, glass enclosed lobby at its base, and a granite paved triangular plaza which contains seasonal flowers, seating and a fountain.

388 Market Street Building (left) was built in 1987 by Skidmore, Owings & Merrill.  The 24-floor postmodern tower occupies the triangular site to the fullest extent, giving it a "Flatiron Building" look. The point is sleekly rounded and the wide end of the triangular plan is sculpted into a drum shape.
